    <!-- Help dialog - Skew-T -->
    <string name="help_stuve_title">Skew-T log-P diagram</string>
    <string name="help_stuve_summary">The Skew-T diagram shows temperature (red) and dewpoint (blue) soundings on a skewed coordinate grid. Tilted isotherms, dry adiabats (green), moist adiabats (dashed teal), and mixing ratio lines (dotted blue) help assess atmospheric stability.</string>
    <string name="help_stuve_tip_1">Where the temperature line is to the right of the parcel path (dashed), the atmosphere is stable; to the left means instability and convection potential.</string>
    <string name="help_stuve_tip_2">The gap between temperature and dewpoint indicates moisture. Where they meet, clouds form (LCL).</string>
    <string name="help_stuve_tip_3">Dots on the sounding lines mark actual model data levels. Use the time slider to view different hours.</string>

